FULL NEMETIC STRING:
Φ(LifespanEvoDev) = σ(process_regulation|adaptive_dynamics) ∘ ρ(accommodative_flexibility|goal_adjustment) ∘ λ(paradigm_shift|stage_dissolution) ∘ β(recursive_growth|nested_systems) ∘ δγ(biological_substrate|evolutionary_constraint) ∘ μ(regulatory_structure|homeostatic_boundary) + ε | :dynamic_equilibrium

OPERATOR BREAKDOWN:

σ — Air / Aerunik (emphasis: 0.73)
  Process-based regulation as the analytical framework replacing stage categorization.
  Rather than asking "what stage is the organism in?" the process model asks "what
  regulatory dynamics are currently operating, at what scales, and with what adaptive
  outcomes?" This shift from categorical to continuous description mirrors broader
  movements in complexity science. Air captures the abstractive, modeling dimension:
  development as a system of interacting regulatory processes rather than a sequence
  of qualitatively distinct phases.

ρ — Water / Sentaria (emphasis: 0.64)
  Accommodative regulation — the capacity to flexibly adjust goals, strategies, and
  expectations when constraints shift — represents the relational-emotional dimension
  of developmental adaptation. Unlike assimilative regulation (persisting toward
  original goals despite obstacles), accommodative regulation involves genuine
  transformation of desire, expectation, and self-concept. Water captures this
  flexibility: the capacity to flow around obstacles rather than breaking through
  them, adjusting the shape of aspiration to the contours of reality.

λ — Fire / Jvalion (emphasis: 0.68)
  The paradigm shift from stage-based to process-based developmental models
  constitutes a genuine conceptual transformation in developmental psychology.
  Stage models (Piaget, Erikson, Kohlberg) organized development as a sequence
  of qualitatively distinct phases with defined transitions. Process models dissolve
  these boundaries, revealing continuous regulatory dynamics that produce the
  appearance of stages as emergent properties rather than fundamental structures.
  Fire here is the intellectual disruption that reorganizes the field.

β — Wood / Arboriel (emphasis: 0.77)
  The dominant operator. Recursive growth within nested systems — cellular,
  organismic, social, cultural, ecological — defines the core developmental
  dynamic. Each level of organization develops through processes that are
  simultaneously shaped by and shaping the levels above and below. Wood captures
  the organic, branching, elaborating quality of development: not a line but a
  tree, not a stage but a growing system of systems. Stability and change emerge
  from the same recursive regulatory processes operating across multiple scales.

δγ — Earth / Humavita (emphasis: 0.75)
  The biological substrate and evolutionary constraints within which all development
  operates. Evolutionary selection has shaped the regulatory architecture of
  development: genetic programs, epigenetic sensitivity windows, hormonal cascades,
  neural plasticity gradients. Earth grounds the framework in material biology —
  development is not purely psychological but occurs within and through biological
  systems that carry evolutionary history. Adaptation, the core construct bridging
  evolutionary and developmental perspectives, is anchored here.

μ — Metal / Ferrosid (emphasis: 0.70)
  Regulatory structures and homeostatic boundaries that maintain system coherence
  while permitting adaptive change. Development requires both openness to
  environmental input and resistance to destabilizing perturbation. Metal captures
  the structural integrity dimension: the boundaries, thresholds, and feedback
  mechanisms that keep developing systems within viable parameter ranges while
  allowing directional change.

Z-STATE: :dynamic_equilibrium
  Development is neither linear progression toward a fixed endpoint nor random
  variation without direction. It is a continuously self-adjusting system that
  balances stability and change through recursive regulation across nested scales.
  The equilibrium is dynamic: it persists only through constant activity, like a
  bicycle that remains upright only while moving.

TENDENCY: β → 0.77
  Wood leads. This is fundamentally about organic growth within nested systems —
  the recursive, branching, elaborating quality of development that cannot be
  captured by linear models. All other operators serve this central vision of
  development as living system dynamics.
